    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h3>Curcumin Absorption Technologies Compared: How Each Enhancer Works</h3>
      <p>The single most important factor in choosing a turmeric gummy is how it addresses curcumin's notoriously poor bioavailability. Without enhancement, you absorb only 1% of the curcumin you consume. Here is how each technology works and what the clinical data shows.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>BioPerine (Piperine)</strong>
          <p>Absorption boost: 2000% (20x). Mechanism: Inhibits glucuronidation enzymes in the liver and intestinal wall that rapidly metabolize curcumin. The most studied and widely used enhancer. Cost-effective. Found in Nature Made, Goli, Sports Research, and Youtheory.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Water-Soluble Micelle Technology</strong>
          <p>Absorption boost: 4000-18500% (40-185x). Mechanism: Encapsulates lipophilic curcumin in water-dispersible micelles, dramatically increasing solubility in the aqueous GI environment. The most advanced technology available in gummy format. Found in Qunol.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Phytosome (Meriva)</strong>
          <p>Absorption boost: 2900% (29x). Mechanism: Binds curcumin to phosphatidylcholine to create a lipid-compatible complex. Excellent tissue distribution. Currently rare in gummy format — more common in capsules. Supported by over 35 clinical studies.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>No Enhancer (Baseline)</strong>
          <p>Absorption: 1% of oral dose. The majority of curcumin is metabolized in the intestinal wall and liver before reaching systemic circulation. Taking with a fat-containing meal and black pepper food can modestly improve absorption, but not to clinical levels.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128138;</span>
        <p><strong>Practical dosing guide:</strong> Clinical anti-inflammatory benefits are typically observed at 1000mg curcuminoids per day with BioPerine, or 500mg with water-soluble technology. For joint pain, start with the higher end and maintain for at least 8 weeks before evaluating results. For general inflammation management, 500mg with an absorption enhancer taken consistently is the evidence-based minimum.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="warn-box">
        <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
        <p><strong>Drug interactions:</strong> Curcumin has blood-thinning properties and inhibits platelet aggregation. If you take anticoagulants (warfarin, heparin), antiplatelet drugs (aspirin, clopidogrel), or NSAIDs regularly, consult your physician before starting a turmeric supplement. Discontinue turmeric at least two weeks before any scheduled surgery to reduce bleeding risk.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

